---
// src/pages/security.astro
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import NavBlock from "../components/NavBlock.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Security & Trust | Quirgs"
  description="Quirgs security posture — content security policy, data handling, skill distribution, vulnerability reporting, and the governance controls applied to the platform itself."
  terminalPath="~/security"
>
  <NavBlock currentPath="/security/" />

  <div class="line">
    <span class="prompt">admin@quirgs</span><span class="path">~/security</span
    ><span class="text-bright">$</span>&nbsp;cat security.md
  </div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <div class="detail-header">
    <h1 class="text-bright">Security &amp; Trust</h1>
    <p class="tagline">
      How the platform is secured, what it collects, and how to report an issue.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Quirgs is a governance-first platform. The same posture it teaches is
    applied to its own operation. This page documents the security and data
    controls in force on quirgs.com and the skills it distributes.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Data Handling</h2>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    Quirgs collects no personal data. There are no user accounts, no login, and
    no server-side database of visitors. The site is statically rendered and
    served from the edge. Aggregate, privacy-preserving analytics (Cloudflare
    Web Analytics and Google Analytics 4) record traffic patterns only — no
    advertising or cross-site tracking cookies are set. Full detail is on
    the&nbsp;
    <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a>.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Content Security Policy</h2>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    Every page ships a strict Content-Security-Policy with no
    <code>'unsafe-inline'</code> for scripts or styles. The only inline scripts permitted
    are pinned individually by SHA-256 hash; everything else loads from <code
      >'self'</code
    >. Framing is denied (<code>frame-ancestors 'none'</code>), the base URI is
    locked, and HTTP is upgraded to HTTPS. This closes the most common injection
    and clickjacking vectors at the browser level.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Email Authentication</h2>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    The quirgs.com apex domain publishes a strict anti-spoofing configuration: a
    null-MX record, an SPF record that authorizes no senders, a reject-mode
    DMARC policy, and a DKIM record that refuses all keys. Nobody can send mail
    that appears to come from quirgs.com itself. A single dedicated subdomain,
    notify.quirgs.com, is provisioned separately with its own SPF, DKIM, and
    DMARC records to send automated gate notifications — it is fully isolated
    from the apex configuration above.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Skill Distribution &amp; Supply Chain</h2>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    Skills are distributed as open, inspectable source — not opaque binaries.
    Each skill's full instruction text is viewable as a public GitHub Gist
    before you install it. Installing a skill loads its instructions into your
    agent's context, so review the source first; the&nbsp;
    <a href="/transparency/">transparency notice</a> and each skill page link directly
    to that source.
  </p>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    Auto-update is off by default. Once installed, a skill does not change
    underneath you unless you explicitly update it. This is deliberate — you
    control when new instructions enter your environment.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Platform Governance Controls</h2>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    No code or content reaches quirgs.com without explicit human sign-off at a
    defined checkpoint. Every change is reviewed on a feature branch and merged
    by pull request — production is never written to directly. AI assistance
    used in building the platform is disclosed in full on the&nbsp;
    <a href="/transparency/">transparency notice</a>.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Reporting a Vulnerability</h2>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    Quirgs publishes a machine-readable security contact under RFC 9116 at&nbsp;
    <a href="/.well-known/security.txt">/.well-known/security.txt</a>. To report
    a security issue, open a private advisory:
  </p>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <div>
    Security advisory &rarr; <a
      href="https://github.com/unqdlphn/quirgs/security/advisories/new"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener">Report privately on GitHub</a
    >
  </div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">What Quirgs Is Not</h2>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    Quirgs is governance tooling, not a certified compliance authority. The
    skills produce structured analysis, checklists, and draft documents — they
    are not legal advice and not a substitute for qualified counsel or a
    certified auditor. There is no SLA or warranty attached to the free
    registry. Treat skill output as a reviewed draft, not a final determination.
    See the <a href="/terms/">terms of use</a>.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <div>
    Questions? See <a href="/support/">/support/</a>.
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
